i˜«S<?php exit; ?>a:6:{s:10:"last_error";s:0:"";s:10:"last_query";s:105:"SELECT wp_posts.* FROM wp_posts WHERE ID IN (15963,15890,15893,15947,15914,15884,15862,15851,15844,15835)";s:11:"last_result";a:10:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15835";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-16 13:24:07";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-16 01:24:07";s:12:"post_content";s:7324:"<p>People happily recite the mantra that "Content is king" but what does that actually <em>mean</em> for you, the small business boss?</p>
<p>In simple terms it means writing the contentÂ yourÂ consumers want and need to hear. In other words, content that is valuable, succinct and authentic. We've said before that <a title="online is not the place for disingenuous hyperbole" href="http://aboutus.co.nz/lose-the-bs-and-speak-plainly/" target="_blank">online is not the place for disingenuous hyperbole</a>Â (talking crap), and thatÂ <a title="longer is not necessarily better" href="http://aboutus.co.nz/stop-thinking-start-blogging/" target="_blank">longer is not necessarily better</a>.Â Below, founder and CEO of Sage IslandÂ <a title="Mike Duncan" href="http://www.wilmingtonbiz.com/insights/mikeduncan/40" target="_blank">Mike Duncan</a>Â shares his insights on how to turn great content into <a title="SEO" href="http://aboutus.co.nz/glossary/seo" target="_blank">SEO</a> so it can be found by your customers online.</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://www.wilmingtonbiz.com/insights/mike__duncan/copywriting_for_results_the_most_effective_seo_tactics/198">Click here to view original web page at www.wilmingtonbiz.com</a></p>
<p>â€œContent is king.â€ Youâ€™ve no doubt heard this expression and let it guide your web development strategy, but the truth is, creating content is really just the tip of the iceberg. And if youâ€™re churning out content that doesnâ€™t adhere to SEO best practices, you might be wasting your time. Like every other aspect of your business, content development should be part of a strategy. Sage Island has seen many content development trends come and go in our 17-year history, and we know what gets results for todayâ€™s web developers.</p>
<p>There are lots of SEO tricks to keep in mind as you develop your copy, which weâ€™ll get to in a moment, but all of it is secondary to the first rule of copywriting: <em>write genuinely good copy</em>. How well optimized your content is wonâ€™t matter if it doesnâ€™t engage readers. As you write your copy, consider your businessâ€™s unique goals. Are you trying to sell something, be informative, or get people through the doors of you business? Your content should be well written and genuinely interesting to the audience you want. Not only will you be helping your potential customers find the information theyâ€™re looking for, but youâ€™re also building brand trust with those customers and increasing the likelihood that they will share your content on social media.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Be smart. Be savvy. Be funny. And if you arenâ€™t any of those things, hire a copywriter who is.Â </p>
</blockquote>
<p>Chances are, you want your siteâ€™s content to reach the most relevant audience to increase qualified traffic. So before you sit down to write, your company will need to perform keyword research to figure out how your customers are searching and what your competition is up to. When it comes to your business, you donâ€™t want to blindly guess what your audience responds to. Good keyword research gives you insight into the mind of your potential customers; it allows you to see what kind of language they are using to ask questions, which gives you the opportunity to provide easy-to-find solutions.Â </p>
<p>So, what should you do with keyword research once you have it? Use it wisely. Knowing top-ranking keywords doesnâ€™t give you permission to write like a robot. Include top keywords in your contentâ€™s title, but make sure the title is relevant to your content and sounds natural. Keep your title under 55 characters (or 512 pixels) to appear correctly in search engine results. You should also sprinkle keywords throughout your body copy, making sure that your content is still well written and doesnâ€™t sound spammy. Avoid keyword cramming â€“ if your keyword usage is too dense, it can actually count against you on search results (and also alienate your readers). Bear in mind that Googleâ€™s Hummingbird update places renewed importance on long-tail keywords (ex: â€œsize 6 princess cut diamond engagement ringâ€ instead of just â€œengagement ringsâ€). Long-tail keywords have a much higher conversion rate than short-tail ones, so keep this in mind as you are developing goals and crafting copy.Â </p>
<p>Once you have your copy drafted, youâ€™ll want to add internal linking. Internal links are connections between the other pages of your website. When copywriting, include a few hyperlinks to a relevant blog post or page of your site. For best results, link to other internal pages for which you want to increase traffic. It also helps to include keywords within your anchor text (the text that comprises the hyperlink). Simply using phrases like, â€œclick hereâ€ as your anchor text isnâ€™t as beneficial as including phrases containing keywords. Donâ€™t include too many internal links, as it can count against your SEO authority, and make sure to vary your anchor text to let search engines know youâ€™re a real person and not a spam-bot.Â </p>
<p>You can give your site additional SEO power by adding keyword-optimized headings to your content. Such headings can help visually organize your pages and are one of the easiest ways to increase keyword prominence. SEO best practices are very cut and dry on proper on-page structure: your H1 tag should appear first on your page, followed by H2s and H3s. Put your keywords first in your heading tags, and keep it relevant to the copy that follows.Â </p>
<p>Last, but certainly not least, proofread! If users spot a mistake, whether itâ€™s an error in grammar, punctuation or a visual, they may lose trust in your brand. It helps to have a fresh set of eyes on your copy to make sure it is polished and matches the tone of your business.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Remember: write for your readers, but optimize for search engines!</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/mikeduncansageisland_4251442036-e1402880644337.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15837 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/mikeduncansageisland_4251442036-e1402880644337.png" alt="mikeduncansageisland_4251442036" width="100" height="100" /></a>About the Author:</strong>Â <a title="Mike Duncan" href="http://www.wilmingtonbiz.com/insights/mikeduncan/40" target="_blank">Mike Duncan</a> isÂ CEO and founder of<span style="color: #222222;">Â <a title="Sage Island" href="http://www.sageisland.com/" target="_blank">Sage Island</a>,Â a full-scale digital marketing agency. Sage Island quickly has built a powerful reputation through award-winning designs, full-service brand strategy, and internet marketing services. It's aÂ boutique agency with big-agency talent specialising in branding, web design, eCommerce, search and social media strategy, and more.</span></p>
