<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Splendia.com" href="http://www.splendia.com/en/hotel-debrett-auckland.html" target="_blank">Splendia.com</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:25:"Why SEO is Key for Hotels";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:25:"why-seo-is-key-for-hotels";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-16 16:04:11";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-16 04:04:11";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:95:"http://aboutus.co.nz/target/why-seo-search-engine-optimization-is-important-for-hotel-industry/";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:3;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15862";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-17 10:41:17";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-16 22:41:17";s:12:"post_content";s:8939:"<h3>The #WorldCup hashtag</h3>
<p>I've been watchingÂ theÂ <a title="FIFA World Cup Brazil" href="http://www.fifa.com/" target="_blank">FIFA World Cup Brazil</a> with moderate interestÂ -Â set to no doubt increase as the days roll on. (With no Kiwi team to support I'm backing Argentina). But what piqued my interest was seeing Twitter getting behind and promoting (and no doubtÂ getting paid for) a singular <a title="hashtag" href="http://aboutus.co.nz/glossary/hashtag" target="_blank">hashtag</a>: <a title="WorldCup" href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/WorldCup" target="_blank">#WorldCup</a>:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/62NnPg2Ds5w" width="890" height="480" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p>While this makes good business sense, despite Twitter's best efforts to create and manage the #WorldCupÂ hashtag -Â including running promotions on someÂ of the hashtags listed below and dominating the your homeÂ page:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-10.58.26-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15877" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-10.58.26-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 10.58.26 AM" width="1236" height="821" /></a></p>
<p>...as is the way of this democratic channel, numerous other hashtags have sprung up, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><a title="#WorldCup2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23WorldCup2014&amp;src=tyah" target="_blank">#WorldCup2014</a></li>
<li><a title="#WorldCupBrazil" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23WorldCup2014Brazil&amp;src=tyah" target="_blank">#WorldCup2014Brazil</a></li>
<li><a title="#FIFAWorldCup" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23FifaWorldCup&amp;src=tyah" target="_blank">#FIFAWorldCup</a></li>
<li><a title="#FIFA2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23FIFA2014&amp;src=tyah" target="_blank">#FIFA2014</a></li>
<li><a title="#FIFA2014WORLDCUP" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23FIFA2014WORLDCUP&amp;src=tyah" target="_blank">#FIFA2014WORLDCUP</a></li>
<li><a title="#Brazil2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Brazil2014&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#Brazil2014</a></li>
<li><a title="Brasil2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Brasil2014&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#Brasil2014</a></li>
<li><a title="#Bresil2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%20%23Br%C3%A9sil2014&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#BrÃ©sil2014</a></li>
<li><a title="#CM2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%20%23CM2014&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#CM2014</a></li>
<li><a title="#wm2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23wm2014&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#wm2014</a></li>
<li><a title="#Copa2014" href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Copa2014&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#Copa2014</a></li>
</ul>
<h3>Twitter as #WorldCupÂ publisher</h3>
<p>Twitter outlines how to be part of its own #WorldCup feverÂ <a title="here" href="https://about.twitter.com/what-is-twitter/world-cup" target="_blank">here</a>. Its offering includes changing your profile pic and headerÂ image to the colours and brandingÂ of your preferred team, followÂ real time game action, get behind the scenes with teams and, of course, share and tweet using the #WorldCup hashtag.</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.13.49-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15872" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.13.49-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 9.13.49 AM" width="1217" height="873" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.45.50-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15864" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.45.50-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 9.45.50 AM" width="967" height="865" /></a></p>
<p>Has it worked? Early days yet with the FIFA World Cup not yet a week in action, but a quick snapshot (admittedly during one of the less popular games) in New Zealand the trending hashtag is #WorldCup2014 with #WorldCup not featuring on the leaderboard:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.50.36-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15865" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.50.36-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 9.50.36 AM" width="285" height="256" /></a></p>
<p>While in Auckland itÂ featuresÂ in third place:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.52.29-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15866" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.52.29-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 9.52.29 AM" width="288" height="236" /></a></p>
<p>AndÂ worldwide, the #WorldCup hashtag hasn't even made the top 10 (at the time of writing), although the <a title="#USAvsGhana" href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/USAvsGhana" target="_blank">#USAvsGhana</a>Â game takes top billing:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.54.33-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15867" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.54.33-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 9.54.33 AM" width="285" height="257" /></a></p>
<p>This is the first time I recall seeing <a title="a bespoke page dedicated to a hashtag" href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/WorldCup" target="_blank">a bespoke page dedicated to a hashtag</a> and I like it:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.58.32-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15868" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-9.58.32-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 9.58.32 AM" width="1663" height="931" /></a></p>
<p>Being able to click on View Match...</p>
<p>.<img class="alignnone wp-image-15870 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-10.02.11-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 10.02.11 AM" width="218" height="184" /></p>
<p>...and launch straight into a global <a title="hashtag feed" href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/GHAvsUSA" target="_blank">hashtag feed</a> of the game makes great sense:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-10.08.01-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15871" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-17-at-10.08.01-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-17 at 10.08.01 AM" width="1663" height="932" /></a></p>
<p>I thinkÂ this move by Twitter isÂ a smartÂ contribution to online publishing via social media. It's great for football fansÂ and lay-viewers alikeÂ on Twitter who are out and about, on public transport, between meetings, or sitting at a desk being able toÂ keep one eye on the score boardÂ andÂ on-the-field action, andÂ the other on their excel spreadsheet.</p>
<h3>So... can you control a hashtag?</h3>
<p>I think the answer is no; no one entity (even Twitter) can control a hashtag - even if they own the channel. I think Twitter has stomped in with a great publishing ideaÂ and has all the tools to back it by creating hashtag feed pages. But ultimatelyÂ people will tweet what they want, and this alters from country to country.</p>
<p>Twitter has however created a compelling reason to join TwitterÂ and a reason to connect with Twitter when the game is on, likelyÂ its mainÂ campaignÂ goals.Â So regardless of success of the #WorldCup hashtag, Twitter gets big tick from me. I also like that despite having what apears to be all theÂ might (and money), Twitter is still not the boss of Twitter - we are!</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15786 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg" alt="belinda" width="100" height="100" /></a></strong></p>
<p><strong>About the Author</strong>:Â <a href="nz.linkedin.com:in:belindanash">Belinda Nash</a> is the Content and Community Manager for About Us, Head of Social Media at <a href="http://www.socialize.co.nz/">Socialize</a>, Advisor to the <a href="http://www.keanewzealand.com/">Kea New Zealand</a> Global Board and is a Council Member for the <a href="http://www.peace.net.nz/">New Zealand Peace Foundation</a>. She has 20+ years experience in media and communications,Â establishedÂ AUT University's social media presence, and has worked with some of New Zealand's most prominent companies. Belinda writes her own blog <a href="iheartprocrastination.co">here</a>.</p>
