<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Lauren Gillespie" href="http://lauren-gillespie.blogspot.co.nz/2011/05/cheater-moms.html" target="_blank">Lauren Gillespie</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:30:"Social Media Buzzwords to Know";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:30:"social-media-buzzwords-to-know";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-26 09:18:18";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-25 21:18:18";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:71:"http://aboutus.co.nz/target/how-to-use-social-media-for-small-business/";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:7;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15914";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-23 12:08:11";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-23 00:08:11";s:12:"post_content";s:5647:"<p>This weekend I hadÂ coffee with an extremely astute 96-year-old woman (aÂ Jewish woman who in 1941 escaped the holocaust in Europe while her entire family perished), her 60-something, extremely well-travelled son and my 76-year-old mother. The three were puzzling over "technology" concernedÂ chiefly aboutÂ being "left behind". In my mother's case, this is not true.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>She has an iPhone and an iPadÂ (which she syncs with iCloud), a Kindle, a laptop and a desktop PC. She actively uses Facebook, Facebook Messenger, YouTube, Skype and Shazm, Googles <em>everything</em> from recipes to directions, downloads information from Wikipedia, reads global news apps on her iPad,Â and uses Snapchat, Pinterest and Instagram (although less frequently). The others are active users of email and mobile phones.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>During our conversation, myÂ mother recalled when she was young makingÂ a "toll-call" to New PlymouthÂ from Woodville in the Manawatu meantÂ contacting the exchange and putting in a request, which may or may not have been granted that evening or the next. Today, she marvels that she can send my sister, who is currently in Paris, a messageÂ in Facebook Messenger or send a picture in Snapchat and sheÂ replies immediately. She also is staggered that kids in school today are preparing for careers that do not yet exist (in fact, this is as true of current university students, so fast is the pace of change).</p>
<h3>The point of social media</h3>
<p>What stood out for me in this chat was the emphasis the three placed on the <em>technology</em>Â rather thanÂ the <em>purpose</em> of these tools and channels.Â Our use of technology is fundamentallyÂ about <strong>connecting, communicating, belonging</strong> and in the case of civil revolution, <strong>making change happen</strong>. And none of this is new; these ways of being are historically aboutÂ our survival as humans. Yes, social media isÂ one means of <em>how</em> we achieve connection, communication, belongingÂ and changeÂ but they are not <em>why</em> we do it. And the secret to technological change lies in the why.</p>
<p><span class="Apple-style-span">Fundamentally, evolution of technology is about making lives better.Â <em style="font-style: italic;">How</em>Â is by connecting, communicating, belonging and making change happen, andÂ <em style="font-style: italic;">What</em>Â is by using tools and channels such as smartphones, tablets and Twitter, Facebook, LinkedIn, Wordpress and more.</span></p>
<p>Yes, the technology is alwaysÂ changing, and we can choose to adapt or not, but ultimatelyÂ <em>it will never pass us by</em>. We will always need to connect with our world, communicate, belong and be part of change, and this will drive our desire to jump on one social media channel or another and get the technology to support it (sooner or later).Â </p>
<h3>Being talked <em>at</em> vs. beingÂ talked <em>with</em></h3>
<p>I then suggested that this evolution of tools and channels is a <em>good</em> thing; thatÂ <span class="Apple-style-span">social media has hailed in an era of human andÂ brand<strong> authenticity</strong></span>. In the case of being human, the longer you're in social media the harder it would be to sustain falsehoods. You cannot lie in LinkedIn for example, because someone in a workplace youÂ professed to work atÂ will call you out.Â </p>
<p>The best bit, is that<strong> every voice inÂ social media is equal</strong>. AÂ brand can't just advertise and tell us that it has great products and services; they mustÂ deliver. If there is a mis-match in a brand's claims, people using social media will share their experienceÂ of usingÂ aÂ product or service: good, bad or ugly. Similarly, in New Zealand, we have the possibility ofÂ direct contact with our politicians, which is unprecedented since lining up to have an audience with a King or Queen. As MP Jacinda Ardern told an Auckland audience this May, tweets come directly to her phone as would a text and she reads every one, adding that it's "impossible" to ignore the collective sentiment within them, though nor would she want to.</p>
<p>So to those afraid of upgrading their "technology" or of using social media - particularly if you're inÂ business - please don't be. These are merely the accessories and extensions of your human experience and ultimately exist because someone wanted to make your life better.</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15786 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg" alt="belinda" width="100" height="100" /></a>About the Author</strong>:Â <a href="nz.linkedin.com:in:belindanash">Belinda Nash</a> is the Content and Community Manager for About Us, Head of Social Media at <a href="http://www.socialize.co.nz/">Socialize</a>, Advisor to the <a href="http://www.keanewzealand.com/">Kea New Zealand</a> Global Board and is a Council Member for the <a href="http://www.peace.net.nz/">New Zealand Peace Foundation</a>. She has 20+ years experience in media and communications, and graduated her Master of Philosophy with first class honours in 2012, and gained her Accreditation in Public Relations in 2006. SheÂ establishedÂ AUT University's social media presence and has worked with some of New Zealand's most prominent companies. Belinda writes her own blog <a href="iheartprocrastination.co">here</a>.</p>
<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Apple" href="http://www.apple.com/ipad/business/profiles/bechtel/" target="_blank">Apple</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:33:""Technology": Making Lives Better";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:30:"technology-making-lives-better";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-23 12:08:11";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-23 00:08:11";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:29:"http://aboutus.co.nz/?p=15914";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:8;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15947";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-25 10:15:25";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-24 22:15:25";s:12:"post_content";s:4461:"<p>It's worth turning our heads to our cousins across the ditch when it comes to stories about using the Internet. The stats around small business uptake of the Internet, social media and cloud-based services in AustraliaÂ is similarly low, if not worse in many more remotely located places. We wrote an article this June about how <a title="The Internet has failed small business" href="http://aboutus.co.nz/the-internet-has-failed-small-business/" target="_blank">The Internet has failed small business</a> here in New Zealand. And we will continue to follow this story as this is a <a title="33 billion dollar cost to our economy" href="http://thebigupgradeblog.tumblr.com/post/81415666821/thirty-four-billion-freaking-dollars" target="_blank">33 billion dollar cost to our economy</a>.</p>
<p>ABC's Carl Smith and Clarissa Thorpe share stories on how Ozzie businesses are getting it right.</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/24291487/small-businesses-following-larger-counterparts-to-social-media-abs-data/">Click here to view original web page at au.news.yahoo.com</a></p>
<p>More Australian businesses are advertising their products online and through social media, but smaller companies are reportedly lagging behind.</p>
<p>The latest Australian Bureau of Statistics data shows almost half of businesses have a website or web presence, and just over one quarter are active on social media such as Facebook and Twitter.</p>
<p>But larger companies are outperforming smaller ones in both areas.</p>
<p>In June last year, 98 per cent of businesses with 200 or more staff had an online presence, and two thirds were active on social media.</p>
<p>Although small businesses are starting to move online, many say the time commitments can be onerous.</p>
<p>Canberra artist Deborah Anne is part of a growing trend of home-based businesses using social media as a voice to generate sales.</p>
<p>Initially she started selling her three-dimensional paper pictures at the markets, through craft website Etsy and on Facebook.</p>
<p>But she is currently building her own website to attract more sales.</p>
<p>"I think people expect it, though not everybody is on Facebook and that's why I need to get the website up and running as well," Ms Anne said.</p>
<p>"I can put photos up there so people have a visual thing to see what I'm all about. I've had contact from people all around Australia and even internationally."</p>
<p>It is an experience shared by hobby horse maker Michael Holmes who is based in the southern New South Wales village of Bungendore.</p>
<p>He has a large online presence, with profiles on Twitter, Facebook, Etsy and Instagram and an individual business website.</p>
<p>"We get a lot of people enquire online and through Facebook and then come to see us at the markets, to see what the product is like before they actually buy it, especially the large rocking horses," Mr Holmes said.</p>
<p>"The traffic varies. Obviously the month before Christmas is really busy with orders but generally all through the year we might get enquires up to 10 o'clock at night."</p>
<p>Mr Holmes recently joined an art co-op which wants to open a retail store in Canberra later this year, but said the online contact would remain an important part of his business model.</p>
<p>"People like that. Everyone asks us if we are local," he said.</p>
<p>"And I find people like to buy from local people, not from big companies, especially when the product is handmade."</p>
<p>Nationally the proportion of companies with a web presence is slowly rising, and social media activity has jumped from 18 per cent of companies to 26 per cent in the 12 months to June 2013.</p>
<p>The increased online activity is matched with more sales for Australian businesses.</p>
<p>Internet orders during 2012-2013 were worth close to $250 billion, an increase of almost $10 billion from the previous year.</p>
